◊indented-justified{If we look at government agencies around us that stand out as ‘best,’ we will find they consist of cohesive groups of women and men who are ‘turned on’ by something. But by what? Not their paychecks, nor the latest reform gimmicks, but by the very work they are doing: stopping child abuse, fighting forest fires, battling epidemics.}
◊sig{—Charles Goodsell, ◊book{Mission Mystique}*}

◊aside{*Credit for introducing me to this quote goes to ◊link["https://danhonig.info" "Dan Honig,"] who also features it on his website. It captures the human element of governance that has long motivated my work.}
I am a first-year Ph.D. student and Ashford Fellow in Government and Social Policy at ◊link["https://www.gov.harvard.edu/people/graduate-students/" "Harvard University."] I am also an affiliate of the ◊link["https://caps.gov.harvard.edu/" "Center for American Political Studies."] I came to graduate study by way of law, after working in various roles across the federal government — in the executive branch, on Capitol Hill, and in the federal judiciary.

I am drawn to questions about how institutions—agencies, legislatures, and the many other bodies that make up the federal government—actually work: how they develop and change over time, how organizational dynamics interact with the formal legal architecture layered on top, and how the component parts shape and reshape one another. My work sits within the American Political Development tradition, and I aim to combine insights from administrative law and organizational theory with historical-institutional methods to take up questions about how the American administrative state has been built, contested, and reshaped over the long run

I came to many of these questions through government lawyering and a longstanding fascination with the people who make up our institutions. Much of what institutions actually do — and how well they do it — turns on something legal categories can’t register: the people inside them, their motivations and limitations, and the organizational cultures that form around them.

Outside of research, I enjoy yoga, drinking more coffee than I should, and spending plenty of time at bookstores. I also care a lot about typography and design—this site being one small outlet for that (see the ◊xref["colophon.html" "colophon"])—and am an avid follower of consumer technology.